Oman’s architecture is out of this world, it’s so naturally beautiful I could cry(!!), the people are so welcoming & its easy (& safe) to do a road trip.  🌵 Mexico: Tacos, surfing, jungle vibes, happy humans, waterfalls, incredible food & pristine beaches. Although I love the East Coast (Tulum etc) I recommend trying to West Coast & including Todos Santos & Sayulita on your itinerary! 🐢 Seychelles: Giant tortoises, crazy blue water, tiny islands to explore & a tropical vibe like no other! 🦘Australia: Snorkel the Great Barrier Reef, eat the yummiest vegan food in Byron Bay, explore the Cape Le Grand National Park in Esperance, rent a boat & sail the Whitsundays & go island / waterfall hopping in Far North Queensland. One of the best countries in the entire world!! 🐠 Maldives: A water wonderland & ultimate heaven on earth. Tiny islands, world class snorkelling / diving & luxury resorts to rival the best in the world! #bucketlistadventures #2023travel #2023goals #traveltheworld #bucketlisttravel #beautifuldestinations #bucketlisters #liveyourpassion #travelgoal #travelthroughtheworld #traveltok

Could you do it? 90 years old and still making the youngsters look like amateurs. In a tucked-away corner of Romania, where time seemed to have frozen in a poignant dance with tradition, I stumbled upon a living testament to the indomitable spirit of life. A grandma, a matriarch in the heart of her village, carving poetry with a scythe in her “batatura,” the courtyard that cradled generations of stories. This wasn’t just about cutting grass; it was an ode to survival etched in every swing of the weathered scythe. An elderly woman, a silhouette against the backdrop of rolling hills and rustic charm, maneuvering a tool almost as ancient as her. The rhythmic cadence of the blade carving through the grass sang a ballad of resilience that transcended the boundaries of time. It was as if the scythe itself held the secrets of a thousand lifetimes, whispered through the hands of those who had faced hardship head-on. In the heart of Romanian villages, where the air is heavy with the tales of survival and shared history, the elders cultivate more than just crops. Our grandma, with her face etched in lines of laughter and wisdom, was a guardian of a fading dialect – the language of resilience, of grit. The scythe, a silent protagonist in this tale, became a bridge connecting the elderly to the present, a tool passed down like an heirloom, carrying the weight of memories in its worn blade.  As she honed that blade with a special stone and cleaned it with freshly cut grass, it wasn’t just about maintaining a tool; it was a ritual, a communion with a way of life that had weathered storms and stood resilient against the test of time. Have you ever seen this before? Wander deep into the untamed heart of the Carpathian wilderness, where the air pulses with the primal vibes of a true king—meet cerbul, the stag. This beast, a living emblem of unbridled beauty, roams Romania’s wild landscapes, casting an ancient spell on those who dare to step into its kingdom. Picture the stag, a majestic silhouette against the backdrop of lush undergrowth, its antlers soaring into the heavens. It moves with the swagger of a guardian of the wild, a noble entity that demands respect with every elegant stride. Witness the spectacle as it sheds and regrows its antlers—a natural show that echoes the rhythmic pulse of these ageless forests. As this majestic creature traverses the rugged terrain, it carries more than just its imposing physicality. It’s a living legend, woven into the very soul of Romania through tales and folklore. The stag isn’t just a symbol of the wild; it embodies resilience, strength, and the delicate interplay between humanity and the wild unknown. Encounters with the cerb forge a connection to the primal spirit of the Carpathian wilderness—a symphony where history’s echoes harmonize with nature’s unyielding grace, creating a rhythm that resonates with every beat of the heart. How would you articulate the essence of the stag? Is it the most light weight? No.  Will it do the job? Yes 🙌🏼  Hiking the highly sort after Jatbula Trail in June and needed to upgrade a few pieces of my gear.  I really wanted to invest in something like sea to summit, MSR or Big Agnes but the budget didn’t allow this year.  However, I’ve picked up this banger from @Anaconda  It’s the Mountain Designs Redline 2P 3 season tent.  I use the wide Alton Goods sleeping pad and it fits that and a slimmer pad but it’s a tight squeeze. I am travelling with a friend so we’ll see how that goes but usually it’s just me and my doggo @Natalya & Hayda  Initial thoughts are that even without actually reading the instructions it was simple to set up in only 5 mins. Has great head room so it’s a tent you can sit up in. Has great ventilation that I can see. It is on the heavier side at 2.1kgs but I’ll be sharing the load on it for the first trip.  #hiking #hikingadventures #hikingwithdogs #jatbulatrail #hikingaustralia #backpackinggear #backpackingadventures #backpackingaustralia #hikingtent #backpackingtent #girlswhohike #girlbackpacker #girlshike #girlswhocamp #cuinthent

After 1 month in Sri Lanka, not including flights, this is what we’ve spent per person… 🏠 £143 on accommodation - less than £5 per night on average! 🛺 £64 on transport which includes buses, trains and tuk tuks 🍜 £437 on food - £14.50 per day on average! 🐘 £82 on activities which includes our safari and other small admission fees 💊 £32 on miscellaneous, which covers Kitt’s tattoo and random bits from the pharmacy  📞 £19.30 each on phone data for the month So, the grand total spend for Sri Lanka was £777 per person, which takes us to a fraction over £25 per person per day over 30 days!  TIPS: ✨A room based on 2 people sharing was nearly always cheaper than a hostel (if you can go without aircon, this saves $$ too!) ✨ Buying train tickets are cheaper at the station than online platforms such as 12Go - buy ahead of time to avoid them selling out! ✨ This one’s a given, but opt for local and street food to save pennies ✨ ‘Pickme’ is a very cheap way of getting taxis in Sri Lanka, and any public transport is extremely low cost! ✨ We use ‘Get Nomad’ for our phone data on an eSim - this saves time and effort (compared with local sim) and easy to top up ✨ Lots of places in Sri Lanka charge for foreigners to enter such as parks. Even some temples would charge 15x the price of locals. Often we would find other things to do that weren’t necessarily on ‘top 10’ lists How did we do?! Could you do it? 90 years old and still making the youngsters look like amateurs. In a tucked-away corner of Romania, where time seemed to have frozen in a poignant dance with tradition, I stumbled upon a living testament to the indomitable spirit of life. A grandma, a matriarch in the heart of her village, carving poetry with a scythe in her “batatura,” the courtyard that cradled generations of stories. This wasn’t just about cutting grass; it was an ode to survival etched in every swing of the weathered scythe. An elderly woman, a silhouette against the backdrop of rolling hills and rustic charm, maneuvering a tool almost as ancient as her. The rhythmic cadence of the blade carving through the grass sang a ballad of resilience that transcended the boundaries of time. It was as if the scythe itself held the secrets of a thousand lifetimes, whispered through the hands of those who had faced hardship head-on. In the heart of Romanian villages, where the air is heavy with the tales of survival and shared history, the elders cultivate more than just crops. Our grandma, with her face etched in lines of laughter and wisdom, was a guardian of a fading dialect – the language of resilience, of grit. The scythe, a silent protagonist in this tale, became a bridge connecting the elderly to the present, a tool passed down like an heirloom, carrying the weight of memories in its worn blade. As she honed that blade with a special stone and cleaned it with freshly cut grass, it wasn’t just about maintaining a tool; it was a ritual, a communion with a way of life that had weathered storms and stood resilient against the test of time. Ich möchte ehrlich zu euch sein. Hätte mir vor 5 Jahren jemand gesagt, dass mit seinem Partner zu reisen genau so eine schöne Erfahrung sein kann wie alleine, hätte ich das nicht geglaubt. Als Alleinreisende wollte ich meine Unabhängigkeit, keine Kompromisse machen und meine Freiheit. Ich hatte all das und trotzdem hat es mich persönlich irgendwann nicht mehr erfüllt. Ich wollte mein Glück teilen. Meine Erlebnisse teilen und meine Erinnerungen. Wenn du nach einer Reise nach Hause kommst und eine Geschichte erzählst, die nur du erlebt hast, wird sie zuhause niemanden so mitreißen wie denjenigen, der sie mit dir zusammen erlebt hat! Sie wird euch für immer verbinden und eure gemeinsame Erinnerung bleiben ❤️ #coupleswhotravel #traveltogether #travelgirl #travellife #vacations #travelgoals #creativetravelcouples #naturephotography #traveltips #travelcommunity #travelislife #seetheworld #travelcouplegoals #adventurecouple #backpackingcouple #backpacksoutheastasia #backpackingadventures #solotraveler #srilanka2024 #backpackingsrilanka

What is the story of Zaharia, 82, a tale that cannot find justice in mere fleeting images? A generation born before and around World War Two, they have endured unyielding toughness throughout their lives, carrying it with them until the very end. Wars, famines, communism—these trials have left just a handful of them behind. But as a nation, have we failed to protect them and provide the closure they deserve? In the villages where the young have departed to seek work in bustling cities or foreign lands, a poignant silence now lingers. Once vibrant communities, these villages embody a fading way of life. The simplicity of days spent tending to fields, the joyous gatherings celebrating harvests, and the warm hearths that nurtured tight-knit families have all waned with time. Now, the elders remain, reminiscing about a past that seems distant and unreal to the younger generations who have chosen different paths. The old ways, deeply rooted in tradition and close-knit bonds, now struggle to survive in the face of modernity's relentless advance. The resilience of these villagers stands as a testament to their enduring spirit, forged through enduring the darkest days of history. Yet, as they bear witness to the departure of their youth, a question lingers: Will the stories of their struggles and the beauty of their traditions find a place in the hearts of those who have moved on? Und vieles hier ist anders, als zuhause in Deutschland, weshalb manches ungewohnt für uns war und wir uns auch in dieser kurzen Zeit nicht dran gewöhnen konnten oder wollten.  Hier unsere 3 Dinge, die wir nicht vermissen werden.  Nr.1 das Plastik am Strand, auch Sri Lanka ist hiervon nicht verschont geblieben und an vielen Ecken wird Plastikmüll angespült. Leider wird auch beim Einkaufen bzw Alltag noch sehr viel Plastik verbraucht. Nr.2 häufig hatten wir beim Essen Sandkörner zwischen den Zähnen. Wir vermuten, dass es oft von den Frühlingszwiebeln bzw. dem Lauch kam. Das tat schon manchmal beim plötzlichen aufbeißen sehr weh. Nr. 3 die Busse dort waren wirklich verrückt und wir hatten teilweise echt Angst vor ihnen. Sie hupen direkt neben dir als Fußgänger mit völlig übertönten Hupen, das sorgt richtig für Adrenalinausschüttung. Ja so ein Urlaub in einem fremden Land bringt auch neue Erfahrungen und dafür sind wir trotzdem dankbar, auch wenn wir sie definitiv nicht vermissen werden. #coupleswhotravel #traveltogether #travelgirl #travellife #vacation #travelgoals #creativetravelcouples #naturephotography #traveltips #travelcommunity #travelislife #seetheworld #travelcouplegoals #adventurecouple #backpackingcouple #backpacksoutheastasia #backpackingadventures #solotraveler #shareexperiences #sorrytosay

Have you experienced dor de Romania? It's a sentiment that can sneak up on you, even if you've never stopped to think about it. It's a kind of homesickness that transcends borders and passports, reaching deep into your soul, stirring up a profound yearning for a place you might not even call home. It's that feeling of longing that descends when you hear a Romanian folk song, the haunting melodies and poetic lyrics pulling at your heartstrings. It's the aroma of mămăligă and sarmale wafting from a kitchen, making you crave a taste of a culture you've only glimpsed through stories and recipes. It's the wistful daydreams of strolling through the historic streets of our towns, admiring the timeless architecture and feeling like you've returned to a place you've never been. The dor de Romania can be experienced by anyone who has been captivated by the country's rich history, its breathtaking landscapes, and the warmth of its people. It's an inexplicable connection that draws you in, making you feel like a part of this extraordinary tapestry of culture, traditions, and natural beauty. Whether you're a Romanian living abroad or a traveler who has been touched by the magic of this land, the dor de Romania is a testament to the enduring allure of a country that has left an indelible mark on your heart. It's a reminder that no matter where you are in the world, a piece of your soul will forever reside in the embrace of Romania. Remember Romania loves you, wherever you are! Don't forget that Florida has many natural springs to explore! These two springs are located about 1hr away from Panama City Beach or Destin.  Ponce De Leon Springs- it's $4 per vehicle to get into the park and It's open from 8am until sunset all year. The spring water is 68 degrees Fahrenheit all year round so it is chilly! I saw people bring tubes with umbrellas to float around here and thought that was such a good idea! There are nature trails you can walk around as well.  Morrison Springs County Park- this spot is near Ponce De Leon and has more of a natural feel to it. It's a popular spot for diving and even has a small cave divers can go into! This is a great spot to kayak too. It includes a diving dock, boat ramp, and boardwalks. It's free to visit!  This was my favorite thing we did on our last Florida trip! Kennst du diesen Ort? Ta Prohm, auch bekannt als der Tomb-Raider-Tempel ist eine verlassene Tempelanlage aus dem 12. Jhdt im Westen Kambodschas nahe der Stadt Siem Reap. Der Tempel, welcher ursprünglich als Kloster und Universität diente, ist bekannt für seine einzigartige Atmosphäre. In dieser Anlage verbindet sich die alte Stätte mit der Natur auf spektakuläre Weise. Gigantische Bäume, unter anderem Würgefeigen wachsen mittlerweile auf den Mauern und haben große Teile des Bauwerkes mit Ihren kräftigen Wurzeln umschlungen. Ta Prohm wurde im Vergleich zu anderen Tempeln nicht restauriert, um die Ursprünglichkeit beizubehalten. Dank dieser Verschmelzung mit der Natur, diente er 2001 als Kulisse für das Videospiel Tomb Raider und die Abenteuer von Lara Croft. I'll be reviewing running routes from all over the world. Running has been my daily ritual for the past ten years, helping me through some tough times. For the last fourteen months, I've been on an incredible journey across sixteen countries, and no matter where I am, running is a must for me. However, I've noticed a lack of detailed information about running routes, especially in less-traveled locations. That's why I'm creating a series of videos reviewing hundreds of different runs from various places around the globe. In each video, I'll share insights about the location and the route itself. I'll only feature routes I'd personally recommend—whether they're fast, flat, and long, or a challenging uphill with breathtaking views.  These routes aren't just great runs; they're also fantastic ways to explore new places. If any of the routes catch your eye, just comment "run" on the video, and I'll share the Strava route with you. You don't need to be super fit or fast to try these routes—I'm not! I do enjoy long distances, so you'll find everything from 5Ks to marathons in my reviews. Next stop? Bulz, sausages, mici, and a winter voyage that transcends mere travel. Imagine the Mocănița, a roaring dragon of steam, slicing through the snowy realms of Bucovina. The rhythmic symphony of the wheels on frost-kissed tracks is the overture to a journey that promises not just sights but an unforgettable culinary odyssey. As the train whispers to a halt at the next station, you're not just met with steam but the intoxicating scent of grilling bulz, savory sausages, and the unmistakable aroma of mici, sizzling and beckoning. Stepping into this frost-kissed station is stepping into a gastronomic fairytale. The vendors, clad in layers against winter's embrace, present the very essence of Bucovina's culinary soul. The bulz, a grilled polenta parcel stuffed with a medley of cheese, bacon, and spices, is a hearty embrace in a single bite. The sausages, kissed by flames, offer a smoky serenade that harmonizes with the crisp winter air. And then there are the mici – those juicy, seasoned meaty treasures that are a cultural emblem in Romania. Embrace the full spectrum of this culinary adventure by pairing your feast with a steaming cup of mulled wine or a bold sip of tuică, the local plum brandy. Let the warmth radiate from your belly to your soul as you immerse yourself in this winter tableau. The Mocănița isn't just a train ride; it's a passage through the heart of Bucovina's flavors. If you're ready to swap conventional travel for an epicurean escapade, let the Mocănița in winter be your chariot through a feast on the move. Tag a friend and get onboard the Mocănița for your next winter adventure! Could you do it? 90 years old and still making the youngsters look like amateurs. In a tucked-away corner of Romania, where time seemed to have frozen in a poignant dance with tradition, I stumbled upon a living testament to the indomitable spirit of life. A grandma, a matriarch in the heart of her village, carving poetry with a scythe in her “batatura,” the courtyard that cradled generations of stories. This wasn’t just about cutting grass; it was an ode to survival etched in every swing of the weathered scythe. An elderly woman, a silhouette against the backdrop of rolling hills and rustic charm, maneuvering a tool almost as ancient as her. The rhythmic cadence of the blade carving through the grass sang a ballad of resilience that transcended the boundaries of time. It was as if the scythe itself held the secrets of a thousand lifetimes, whispered through the hands of those who had faced hardship head-on. In the heart of Romanian villages, where the air is heavy with the tales of survival and shared history, the elders cultivate more than just crops. Our grandma, with her face etched in lines of laughter and wisdom, was a guardian of a fading dialect – the language of resilience, of grit. The scythe, a silent protagonist in this tale, became a bridge connecting the elderly to the present, a tool passed down like an heirloom, carrying the weight of memories in its worn blade. As she honed that blade with a special stone and cleaned it with freshly cut grass, it wasn’t just about maintaining a tool; it was a ritual, a communion with a way of life that had weathered storms and stood resilient against the test of time. Details down here 🙋🏻‍♀️ If you want to experience something different you don’t wanna miss out this little hidden gem in Cebu Philippines  You’ll have to drive up the mountain in either a car but I prefer to be on a scooter  The journey will take around 1h but it will be worth it! You’ll arrive to Little Amsterdam, almost a small town on its own 😅 Each corner of this garden has something different to offer Everything and anything you can only imagine will be here.. You can find windmills, butterflies, birds, mushrooms, rabbits, magicians, a hand which you can take pictures from over looking the beautiful view and much more.  It’s a perfect place to get lost in for a couple of hours  Anyone from adults to kids will for sure have a great time here 🤣 What do you think about this place? This Some kind of tourists in  our existence  The Black Desert is an area of volcano-shaped and widely separated mounds in western Egypt, stretching for around 30 kilometres (19 miles) between the White Desert in the south and the Bahariya Oasis in the north. Basalt sills cover the majority of its mounds, giving them their distinctive black appearance. The Black Desert's mounds, which may reach heights of 100 metres (328 feet), vary in size, composition, height, and shape, with some being black due to iron quartzite and others being more reddish due to iron sandstone. Volcanic hills on the fringes of the Black Desert show that black volcanic dolerite erupted 180 million years ago, indicating the Jurassic era. 1 Its soooo beautiful. It is volcano's lava. When you approach the mountain the lava are balck rocks. When you start walking up the mountain and you approach the summit, you realize that the volcano's lava made the rocks all pressed one against each other. Something phenominal. You just have to wear good climing boots or shoes. Some rocks are slippery. Must be careful. It is the highest summit in the black desert. I have never immagined that a desert can be or have a magical view  2 The Black Desert is located North from the White Desert, closer to Bahariya than Farafra. The name comes from the black volcanic hills and eroded material covering the sand with black stones and powder. The darkness contrasts with what you will experience few dozens of kilometers later, the White Desert, adding to the variety of Egyptian deserts. Winter and early spring nights are pretty chilly, so remember to take a good sleeping bag if you plan camping. Rotorua is a city in the Bay of Plenty Region of New Zealand's North Island. It is sited on the southern shores of Lake Rotorua, from which it takes its name. It is the seat of the Rotorua Lakes District, a territorial authority encompassing Rotorua and several other nearby towns. Kennt ihr diesen Teil in euch, der gerne alles auf einmal machen möchte? Auch wenn das mehr Stress bedeutet. Der Teil der gerne viel mitnehmen möchte und dafür über die eigenen Grenzen geht, statt erst die eigene Batterie aufzuladen und dann wieder Vollgas zu geben Wir wollten heute eigentlich die heiligen Stätte von Angkor Wat besichtigen, nachdem wir gestern Abend erst spät in Siem Reap angekommen waren. Irgendwie hat dann heute Morgen alles etwas länger gedauert und das hat mich schon total gestresst weil es draußen immer wärmer wurde und wir voll in die Mittagshitze gekommen wären. Gleichzeitig ist heute Donnerstag und ich dachte wir sollten auf jeden Fall heute gehen, damit wir nicht in das Wochenende kommen, wo es vermutlich voller wird..  Irgendwann habe ich dann gemerkt, dass es heute einfach anstrengend werden würde (durch die Hitze und wenig Schlaf). Ich habe dann den Gedanken, heute gehen zu müssen, losgelassen. Wir hatten den Zeitdruck nämlich eigentlich gar nicht, sondern ich habe ihn uns gemacht. Danach hat sich alles entspannt und wir haben es einfach auf morgen verschoben, was sicherlich genauso gut werden wird.  Manchmal muss ich einfach den einen Gedanken loslassen der mir Stress macht, dann wird auch alles gut und wir können viel entspannter an die Sache rangehen. Auch falls es morgen voller wird :)  (Ich glaube unsere Capcut Skills werden langsam auf ein neues Niveau angehoben 😃) #mealsome #coupleswhotravel #traveltogether #travelgirl #travellife #vacation #travelgoals #personalities #creativetravelcouples #naturephotography #traveltips #travelcommunity #travelislife #seetheworld #travelcouplegoals #adventurecouple #backpackingcouple #backpacksoutheastasia #backpackingadventures #solotraveler #shareexperiences

Thinking about backpacking +10,000 km from Nairobi to South Africa? It's definitely cheaper than flying and there's a lot of bus options cutting through multiple countries from Kenya all the way to South Africa and back. At the moment there's no bus company doing a direct journey but it's easy enough to go capital city to capital city. In fact, the further south you go the more busing options there are. Here are some basics for any long distance backpacking trip: 1. Be patient- some border crossings will be super fast while others will take a lot of time, some people will not respond to your sense of urgency, some things won't work the way you expect them to.  2. Be flexible- have multiple plans so that you don't get stuck. Cars break down, government officials can be tricky, ailments will throw you off your game... 3. Be ready to jump at opportunities- your legs will swell up or cramp up, your back will be uncomfortable, your butt will ache so take all the breaks you get... including bathroom breaks! 4. Pack light- Take only what you need because hauling bags upon bags everywhere is not the life. 5. Tissue, water or wipes- yes to everything. You'll want to keep fresh while on the road so they come in super handy. 6. Plan ahead- Understand what your expenditure per country will be so that you change cash at the most opportune places. Get the country's sim card for easier comms and good internet. Both can be found at border crossings. Exercise good judgement when dealing with money at all times. 7. Luxury hotel v. Bed and breakfasts- If you need to catch an early morning bus it's easier to find somewhere to stay that's close (walking distance or short taxi ride). Obviously work within your budgets but check online deals as well as ask around for locals to give you recommendations.  8. Interact with locals - They know their environment better than you and the internet. Be open to new connections, spread some good cheer and make the best of all situations. Every trip will have it's specific set of requirements so do some research but all in all, go out there and explore!! #backpackingkenya #backpackingadventures #backpackinglife #travelsouthafrica #travelkenya

What you MUST fix before going 👇🏼Part 1.  Visa is potentially something you’ll need for your backpacking trip depending on how long you’ll spend in each place.  Either you can apply for a Visa On Arrival at the airport as you enter the country or you can apply beforehand at the embassy so it’s already done.  VOA is good if you’re planning on staying for 30 days or less, or you have time to do a visa extension while you’re away. You initially get 30 days which you can extend twice for a total of 90 days in Bali. Normally VOA costs around €30.  The other option is to get a B211A Tourist visa that gives 60 days and can be extended twice for a total of 180 days. This you’ll have to get before you go at the embassy and it costs around €100. #throwback  一提到新西兰很多人就直接联想到蓝天白云，牛羊成群，其实不然，更吸引我的是这个位于太平洋西南部, 由南北两个岛屿组成的主权岛国的人文与历史。接近两个半月新西兰/台湾/冲绳岛背包行尾声，开始和大家回顾一路上的景致与“重心连接Reconnection2” 之“五十五刻” 背包行之点滴,第一站新西兰最大城市-奥克兰🐑🐮🐏🐂🐄🐑🐐 Coming to an end of my 2.5 months NZ/Taiwan/Okinawa “Reconnection 2" backpacking 🥾 . It's time to look back on this amazing journey celebrating 55 years on earth. I started off with Newzealand's  biggest city Auckland for 6 days before I head further North of Newzealand for my 6th Vipassana silent meditation course since I started from 2018, before heading towards South NZ. This video captured random fond memories in Auckland. Lovin the nature always just steps away , nostalgic n rich heritage n culture that was well preserved even in this generation. Even though I LOVED my country , while on the road, I always thought , are we changing too fast , too clean , too systematic from the angle of an artist, but yet too slow, too sterile n even uninventive from an Artiste from entertainment music scene point if view, that's why I like backpacking ,  it allows me to keep questioning myself in the intersection of cross roads meeting different spaces n people .  While some might say there's nothing much in Auckland, but I felt like wise. From a non hiker, sea sports person n non driver , I had a wonderful in Auckland visiting the museums, harbours, bays and beaches. Also visiting nostalgic cinemas and getting lost in the local neighbourhoods was as fun for me. The following are just a few of my favourite museums( they have much more): 1. Auckland War Memorial Museum (ticketed) https://www.aucklandmuseum.com/ one of the most important museum in NZ built in 1920,  exhibition n collections was amazing . 2. There are 3 ways to go from Bangkok to Chiang Mai: by air, by bus and by train. The best way to get from Bangkok to Chiang Mai is to fly which takes 3h 5m and costs approximately ฿1100 - ฿3200. Alternatively, you can take a bus via Sombat Tour, which costs around ฿500 - ฿1100 and takes 9h 12m. And last, but not least you could also take a night train, which costs ฿210 - ฿1600 and takes 10h 5m. I took the night train from Bangkok to Chiang Mai, which was fun and clean! The way back, from Chiang Mai to Bangkok, I took a bus, which was a total "nightmare". The bus was very old and full of cockroaches everywhere. I did not sleep at all that night. So I would recommend you to take a night train or a flight, instead of a bus. Jak się lata pierwszą klasą? Sprawdziłem też cenę biletu. Przyprawia o zawrót głowy! O pierwszej klasie mówi się, że to kwintesencja luksusu. Przygoda zaczyna się już przed wylotem. Pasażerowie mogą zrelaksować się przed w eleganckim saloniku na wygodnych, skórzanych sofach. W cenie biletu na lot pierwszą klasą (kosztuje 15 razy więcej niż bilet w klasie ekonomicznej i 5 razy więcej niż bilet na klasę biznes) znajduje się: Prywatny szofer Dostęp do kilku restauracji Bar z cygarami Strefa ciszy Spa z prysznicem Na powitanie dostałem od obsługi samolotu kawę po arabsku z daktylami. W jej skład wchodzi: woda różana, kardamon i ziarenka kawy. Dla pasażerów pierwszej klasy posiłki przygotowują najlepsi szefowie kuchni. Menu jest równie bogate jak w najlepszych restauracjach z gwiazdką Michelin. Najlepsze jest to, że można zamawiać co się chce, ile się chce i kiedy się chce. Najważniejszy w pierwszej klasie jest komfort pasażera oraz to, że można się poczuć zupełnie prywatnie. Naciskając jeden przycisk „kabina” pasażera, która przypomina mini luksusowy apartament zostaje zamknięta. W środku znajduje się prywatna lodówka, tablet, lusterko, 32-calowy telewizor. Można również odpocząć na fotelu, który po rozłożeniu jest wygodnym łóżkiem. Materiał archwialny z 2019 roku. Cała wersja do zobaczenia na stronie „Dzień dobry TVN”.  #firstclass #firstclassflight #firstclasstravel #pierwszaklasa #samolot #emiratesairlines #emirates #dubaj #piotrwojtasik #ddtvn #luxury #luxurylife #luxurylifestyle #luxurytravel #aesthetic #airport @Emirates

SAKE IN A WOODEN BOX?! UMM... WHAT NOW? 😭🫶🏼 We tried Japanese sake for the first time in Japan, and they served it in a wooden box… overfilled! 😂 We definitely weren’t expecting that and had no idea how to drink it without spilling haha! But wow, the sake was so good, and the whole experience was just amazing. Japanese people really know how to enjoy life. 🙌 💡 Fun fact: In Japan, sake served in a wooden box is called a "masu," and apparently, the overfilling is a sign of generosity and hospitality! 🫶 📍 Tokyo, Japan 🇯🇵 If you’re visiting Japan and looking for things to do in Japan, trying authentic Japanese sake is a must. Add it to your bucket list for a true taste of Japanese culture! 🍶✨ #japan #sake #japantraveltips #traveltok #travelcouple #vlog

Join me today as I fly the 747-400. Not only that, but this is the last one flying in Asiana’s fleet. I don’t know why they’ve kept just one, and I don’t know why they only fly it between Osaka and Seoul these days, but I’m not asking too many questions because it means I get to fly it! I figured out a nice way to get home from Osaka: Seoul is a good place to book cheap business class tickets from, and I found a $1600 Emirates ticket all the way back to Stockholm from there. So tacking on this 747 to the itinerary was a no-brainer, even though this made my trip stretch to 32 hours in total. The things we do to fly special planes eh? Kansai International Airport is built on a massive man-made island out in Osaka Bay, and you have to cross a long bridge to get to it. The airport is in need of a refresh – it looks and feels old and a little neglected.  I’m in seat 3A in the nose of theis 747, what used to be Asiana’s international First Class, but is now sold as business class. Bit of a waste to have all this space on a flight that’s barely over an hour, but I’m going to make the most of it. We get just enough post-sunset light still in the sky for some nice views after takeoff. And they serve a full meal which is quite good. Especially because it comes with gochujang sauce. I also manage three gin & tonics on this flight. That takes some dedication guys. Check out the old-school metallic sink lavs too. Kind of classic and cool! It was a lovely, if too short, flight on the 747. Let me know what you think! Working as a digital nomad in Antigua and Barbuda has the following benefits: •Easy internet access. With an internet speed fixed 20.95 Mbps and mobile 33.80 Mbps, you can work in any part of the world from Antigua & Barbuda, feeling at home or office. •Smooth visa application process. Applying for the Antigua & Barbuda digital nomad visa is fairly easy, and everything is done online. Moreover, you will have to wait only 14 days for an answer. •Tax exemption. As a digital nomad, you are exempt from ping income taxes in Antigua and Barbuda. •Warm climate. With a tropical savannah climate, Antigua & Barbuda has pleasing year-round weather. The best time to visit Antigua & Barbuda is November to April, when it is least rainy and hot. •Delicious cuisine. Antigua & Barbuda has become a food destination because of its fresh seafood, flavored dishes, and top-notch rum. This place is a haven for rum distilleries and sugar plantations. •Leisure activities. In Antigua & Barbuda, you can enjoy a variety of activities. Among the activities you can enjoy are exploring rainforests, swimming with stingrays, biking, kayaking, diving, snorkeling, sailing, and fishing. Do you remember the comforting sounds of grandma’s house? Close your eyes and let nostalgia carry you back to that cherished place, a traditional Romanian village house. Inside, the soul-soothing crackle of wood in the white plastered stove creates a symphony of warmth and anticipation. But it’s not just the sounds; it’s the feelings that stir your heart. Above the stove, by the chimney, can you recall the innocent laughter of a child playing with the house cat, their giggles echoing the joy of carefree days? That child was probably you. The coziness of that moment, the shared warmth, and the bonds of family—aren’t those the feelings that stay with us forever? And then, the aroma of grandma’s cooking. Do you still carry in your memories the smell of dishes prepared with love and generations of know-how? Those unforgettable scents, wafting through the air, have the power to transport you back in time? But here’s the magic of grandma’s house: as you reminisce about those sounds, feelings, and smells, it’s impossible not to ponder the simple joys of childhood. What were your favorite games to play with cousins in the cozy corners of that house? Do you remember the stories and lullabies that lulled you to sleep under that same roof? In the heart of the Romanian countryside, a village stands frozen in time, embraced by the hushed stillness of a golden hour. Maria, a weathered soul with eyes that have seen decades of stories, watches as her four dogs chase each other through the deserted ulita. The scene is like a painting, a masterpiece created by nature itself, with the soft light casting long shadows of traditional wooden fences made of posts and logs that line the path. Amidst the silence, a giant tree spreads its branches wide, offering a sheltering canopy over the ulita. Its gnarled bark and outstretched limbs evoke a sense of timelessness, a silent witness to the ebb and flow of generations. Beneath its shade, an open fire crackles, casting dancing shadows that intertwine with memories etched into the village’s very soul. A pot hangs above the flames, its contents simmering with the essence of traditional flavors, a reminder of the nourishing traditions that sustain the spirit. As the dogs play and the sun dips lower, casting a warm, amber glow on the landscape, Maria finds her place on a weathered bench. The village may be deserted, but it teems with life’s echo, resonating in the breeze that rustles through forgotten corners. Maria’s gaze is one of patient longing, a testament to the enduring spirit of those who remain, tethered to their roots and the stories that once reverberated through these deserted streets. In this quietude, one is compelled to ponder: what led to this emptiness, this haunting beauty of abandonment? Trust me, the scenery is breathtaking 🌳🌄. Now, let me tell you why I made this trip – it’s all about the charcoal by the roadside! There's an old tale that says if you take the charcoal without seeing who sells it, it'll start 'talking' to you when you get home. Yes, you read that right!  But nowadays, things are different. I stopped to ask one of the local women, and she explained that now you just call a number, send the money, and take your charcoal. Easy peasy! Curious, right? Arizona Road Trip 🇺🇸🚗 Day 7: Exploring the iconic Monument Valley! 🌄✨This stunning landscape is part of the Navajo Nation, and the park is owned by the Navajo tribe. The area’s breathtaking red rock formations have been featured in countless films—it’s like stepping into a classic Western! From breathtaking red rock formations to the endless desert horizon, join us on an unforgettable journey through this stunning landscape! 🐴🏜️ 💁🏼‍♀️ Travel tip: The scenic drive is a must-do, but it’s only for SUVs— the road is really rocky and rough, so be prepared for a bumpy ride! But trust me, it’s worth it!  Also, make sure to check the park’s opening and closing times ⌚️—usually, you need to enter between 5 and 6 PM to catch the sunset! 🌄✨ #MonumentValley #travelblogger #travelusa  #roadtrip #route66 #usaroadtrip #usa #travelbucketlist #travel #sunsetview #arizona #roadtripvibes

Have you ventured to Rasnov, a town steeped in the legends of medieval Transylvania? Tucked away within the Carpathian Mountains, Rasnov is a place where history echoes through the narrow streets and ancient fortifications. At the heart of Rasnov stands the impressive Rasnov Citadel, a fortress that has watched over the town for centuries. This towering stone bastion, perched atop a hill, offers breathtaking views of the surrounding landscape. The fortress isn't just a relic of the past; it's a living testament to the resilience of the people who built it to defend against invaders. Rasnov's charm extends beyond its citadel. The town's Old Town, with its quaint houses and cobblestone streets, transports you to a time when horse-drawn carriages clattered through the lanes. Have you ever explored the hidden corners of Rasnov, discovering the stories etched into its walls and streets?  The town's rich history and stunning natural surroundings make it a captivating destination, inviting you to uncover its secrets and embrace its timeless allure. If you haven't yet had the pleasure of visiting Rasnov, isn't it time you embarked on this journey through the ages? Taiwan is giving away free money to tourists 🤑💰 If you’re planning your next trip to Taiwan, make sure to save this video for the best travel hack/tip! 📌 Make sure to register 1-7 days before your scheduled arrival date. 📌 Check to see if you qualify and meet the traveler eligibility  📌 Scan the QR code at the booth located in the Arrival Hall. 📌 Pick a lucky coin and find out if you’re a lucky winner! 📌 If you are a lucky winner, head towards the counter to redeem your cash card! *Not everyone is a winner, my fiancé didn’t win* I was not able to get an EasyCard (my preference) but received an iCash card instead! Make sure to check the website to see what places accept iCash, but don’t worry, 7-11, MRT, Carrefour, etc., take it. I ended up having remaining money left over since transportation by MRTA in Taiwan is super affordable. The animals live freely under care and are NOT drugged! About Serval Wildlife and the animals taken from their website: "Our sanctuary is over 1000 acres, prepared in phases and in accordance with the needs of our animals 50 acres at a time. Animals are ethically obtained from zoos & injured animals from the wild with the aim of instilling natural behaviors and eventually rehabilitating them into the wild with the assistance of TAWA and TAWIRI. The animals that reside within our wildlife sanctuary are owned by the Tanzanian Government and often brought to us by TAWA as orphans or injured wildlife. We treat and train our animals to prepare them for release into their natural habitat within TANAPA protected parks. Our wildlife sanctuary also doubles as an endangered species reintroduction platform to translocate animals to parts of its natural range where populations have significantly declined or been lost. Aiming to establish a viable population within translocated areas. Our most recent animals for release are our lions. Brought to us from other zoos due to being rejected by their mother at a very young age. Upon arrival these animals were in poor condition, we have trained them and nursed them back to health. With assistance from TAWA these animals are being softly released from captivity into their natural habitat. https://www.servalwildlife.com/about ❤️❤️❤️ #tanzania #africa #afrika #hakunamatata #kilimanjaro #hausatiktok #norsktiktok #lionking #servalwildlife #safari #solotravel #fyp #fypage

Do you remember the comforting sounds of grandma’s house? Close your eyes and let nostalgia carry you back to that cherished place, a traditional Romanian village house. Inside, the soul-soothing crackle of wood in the white plastered stove creates a symphony of warmth and anticipation. But it’s not just the sounds; it’s the feelings that stir your heart. Above the stove, by the chimney, can you recall the innocent laughter of a child playing with the house cat, their giggles echoing the joy of carefree days? That child was probably you. The coziness of that moment, the shared warmth, and the bonds of family—aren’t those the feelings that stay with us forever? And then, the aroma of grandma’s cooking. Do you still carry in your memories the smell of dishes prepared with love and generations of know-how? Those unforgettable scents, wafting through the air, have the power to transport you back in time? $0.60 Street Food in Kolkata, India 🇮🇳 I was exploring the Maidan Market in Kolkata, West Bengal when I saw some busy street food area. Whatever they were cooking looked and smelled delicious, and was very popular. There were tables full of locals enjoying this local snack. It was so busy that I had to share a table with a local Bengali family, who were very nice and explained to me that this food is called Mughlai Paratha. It's something like a cross between a pancake and an omelette and was very tasty! I'd definitely eat it again. #India #Kolkata #WestBengal #Desi #Travel #SoloTravel #TravelAdvice #BudgetTravel #Bengali #IndianFood #IndianCuisine #StreetFood #DesiFood

Mango Ice Cream Bun in Manila, Philippines 🇵🇭 I visited the Salcedo weekend market in Makati, Manila where I found this vendor selling mango ice cream. The local way is to eat it in a bread bun rather than a cone, so that's what I got. One bun filled with mango ice cream cost 50 pesos, about $0.90 USD. That's a lot more than ice cream normally costs on the streets in the Philippines, but it's a fancy weekend market in Makati, a rich area of the city. The ice cream tasted very natural, like it had been made with real mango, and was not overly sweet. #Manila #Philippines #Travel #TravelVlog #SoloTravel #StreetFood #FilipinoFood #FilipinoCuisine #IceCream

Tiana’s Palace 🐸 Maybe don’t mosey on down to this spot! I was hoping this wasn’t going to be the case, but here is my brutally honest review! Tiana, I still love you, I just KNOW you are a better cook than this!  Tiana’s Palace 📍Disneyland DO NOT, I repeat, DO NOT mobile order here if you want a good presentation for you food. Wait in line and enjoy the inside of the building. The idea of mobile ordering and the pick up window here is nice, but you don’t get to go inside to see all the wonderful work the Imagineers did, and your food will come in a ridiculous amount of plastic.  🍽️ Lunch and Dinner – 10:00 AM to 9:00 PM The One Entree I would Suggest: 🐸Cajun Spiced Half Chicken ➡️ brushed with BBQ Sauce served with Baked Macaroni and Cheese & Coleslaw 💵$19.49 My “Skippable” Entrees: 🐸7 Greens Gumbo with Chicken & Andouille Sausage ➡️ White Beans, Okra, Yams, Sweet Potatoes and Heirloom Rice 💵$16.99 🐸Muffuletta Sandwich ➡️ Mortadella, Salami, Rosemary Ham, Cheddar, Provolone and House-made Olive Relish on Toasted New Orleans Sesame Seed Bread, served with Red Beans & Rice and House-made Pickles 💵$14.99 🐸Gulf Shrimp and Grits ➡️ simmered in Creole Sauce with Cheesy Grits 💵$17.49 Dessert: 🐸House-filled Beignet ➡️ Featuring Lemon Ice Box Pie Filling topped with Lemon Glaze 💵$4.49 Why did we have to do this to Tiana, this had the potential to be so good and just really missed the mark. I understand trying to cater to a larger audience, but don’t sacrifice taste if you are putting Tiana’s name behind it!  #disneyland #disneylandfood #disneyeats #tianaspalace #disneyfoodie #traveltok #foodreview

5 fascinating things about driving in italy 🇮🇹📍 01:- ZTL Zones (Limited Traffic Zones): Many Italian cities, especially historic centers like Rome and Florence, have Zona a Traffico Limitato (ZTL), restricted areas where only residents, taxis, and delivery vehicles can enter during certain hours. Tourists often receive fines for unknowingly driving into these zones! 02:- Autostrada Toll Roads: Italy's autostrada highways are well-maintained but are often toll roads. Drivers take a ticket upon entering and pay when exiting, based on the distance traveled. 03:- Speed Cameras and Fines: Italy is strict on speeding, and speed cameras are common on highways and city roads. Speeding fines can be mailed to you even if you're a foreign driver, thanks to plate tracking. 04:- Unique Parking Rules: Parking spaces are color-coded in Italy: white lines are for free parking, blue lines indicate paid parking, and yellow lines are reserved for residents, disabled drivers, or specific vehicles. 05:- Roundabouts with a Twist: In Italy, drivers in roundabouts generally give priority to vehicles entering the roundabout, unless specified otherwise by signage—opposite of what is common in many other countries! #DrivingInItaly  #ItalianRoadTrip  #carculture   #exploreitaly  #roadtripvibes  #travelgoals  #italyadventures  #funfacts  #wanderlust  #traveltips

🇪🇸BARCELONA RECS:  Save the link at the end of this caption  to your Google maps, there’s lots of pinned recommendations from others if you’re going soon!  🍴To eat: •Cañete: squid sandwich & red mullet •Tapeo: sticky asian ribs & sea urchin + shrimp fideuà •El Xampanyet: grilled squid & chorizo tortilla  •Ciutat Comtal: broken eggs with iberico ham •Mikan: cherry tomato bomblets & yuzu butter mushroom •Takumi: black garlic miso ramen  •Bodega Borràs: duck & porcini paella with truffle  •Vinitus: crayfish paella  🏨To stay: •Hotel SOFIA - luxurious 5 stars with pool & spa 10 mins from centre  •Antiga Casa Buenavista - boutique hotel in city centre with rooftop pool •Soho House Barcelona - members hotel in front of the marina 💃🏻To do: •Book an experience!! I did a paella cooking class and it was SO FUN Link here: https://abnb.me/TebIEJU8SBb •La Boqueria Market, go 10-12 in the morning to avoid busy crowds 🥘 •Get the train to Garraf or Sitges and have a day out at the beach, much more beautiful and cleaner than the city’s 🏖️  •Park Güell, book tickets in advance online 🛍️Shopping:  •El Born is the area for local independent brands!!  •Ivori •Röa Clothes & Design •Yümi (cheap & cute jewellery) •Growold  ‼️Tips: •Wear comfy shoes as Barcelona is huge!! I also used the bus which was cheap & clean, you can use contactless but they do take cash after certain hours at night •Avoid Uber, hail the city’s black cabs instead, way cheaper by meter  •ATTENZIONE PICKPOCKET, please get yourself a cross body bag and guard it with your life  https://www.google.com/maps/placelists/list/BF6aoijNW011gRADxQJ16LzDIWCiyQ?g_st=i ##solotravel##travelvlog##barcelona##hotelbarcelona##barcelonaeats##womantraveler##foodreview##dayinthelife##fideua ##whatiate##whattodobarcelona##barcelonabeach##tortilla##soloholiday##barcelonarestaurant##restaurantreview##bestbarcelonaeats##barcelonarecommendations

DOES IT FIT?! 👜 PART 1: 20L 👜 As part of ✨ Luggage Week ✨ I’ll be heading to the one area of the airport that us cheap holiday fans all hate: 😭 THE DREADED BAGGAGE SIZER 😭 ⛓️ Yep, the metal cages you may be asked to fit your bag inside to prove it’s the right size. So let’s discover whether our favourite bags ACTUALLY fit in the space for a SMALL CABIN BAG (that’s the bag size you’re allowed for free on these airlines!) 😬 🆙 We’ll be going up in size so even if you don’t have this exact bag, you’ll be able to get an idea if your bag will squeeze inside. So let’s kick things off with… 👜 20L 👜 40 x 20 x 25cm AKA the ‘viral Ryanair cabin bag’ Which… if we’re honest, is kind of the top end of what you should be allowed to fit in a small cabin bag baggage sizer 😂 Here’s what it’s contending with: ✈️ RYANAIR ✈️ 40 x 20 x 25cm ✈️ EASYJET ✈️ 45 x 36 x 20cm ✈️ WIZZ AIR ✈️ 40 x 30 x 20cm So… DOES IT FIT?! 📣 DROP ME A COMMENT… If you’ve ever used one of these? I see people go up to them at the airport and I am hissing at them to not do it as so often they’re in plain view of the staff 😂😂😂 #travelhack #travelhacks #baggage #luggage #luggagehacks #baggagehacks #ryanairbag #tiktokbag #cabinbag #travelbag

YOU are on holiday, Your ISLAM is NOT on holiday!☪️🕌 - This is firstly a reminder to myself before anyone else! It's common that when on holiday we tend to have a more relaxed and stress free feeling, after all we are there to enjoy ourselves and relax out of our usual work routines, but this this should not effect our Islam! We are forever Muslims and are not taking a holiday from being Muslim! It can sometimes seem difficult when doing excursions and travelling to find time to pray but again Islam is an easy religion, Allah has made it easier for us when we are travelling so much so that most of our prayers are halved, and we can simply put a mat down and carry out our prayer anywhere clean!  This is also why I love travelling to Muslim countries! They may not be perfect, but the majority of the times, you are surrounded by a lot more Masjids and can hear the adhaan for every salah out loud! Halal food is prominent everywhere! The majority of the locals wear the hijaab and cover their satr and just being around all of this, and that atmosphere helps us be more wary and stay steadfast on our Deen! May Allah help and guide us all!🤲🏻 - #halaltourism #halaltour #halaltravel #islam #muslim #islamicquotes #travelinspiration #travel #travelblogger #travelgram #luxurytravel

Craving Kürtőskalács? Did you know it was actually first made in Romania? Let’s uncover the heartwarming tale behind this treat. Originating in Transylvania, Kürtőskalács, or Chimney Cake, was crafted by the Hungarian-speaking Székelys. Dating back to 1679, the first record appeared in Úzdiszentpéter village. Once reserved for special occasions, it now embodies Romania’s sweet history Imagine sweet yeast dough spun, wrapped around a cone-shaped spit, rolled in sugar, and roasted over charcoal. The sugar caramelizes, forming a luscious, shiny crust. The name “Kürtőskalács” reflects its chimney-like shape. As it evolved, it underwent name changes, finally settling on “kürtőskalács” in the 20th century. This cake’s journey is a culinary masterpiece, telling the story of the region’s heritage. Over time, this treasure’s reputation spread, captivating locals and travelers alike. Beyond its origins, Kürtőskalács stands as a testament to the artistry of European cuisine. So, as you savor every bite, remember, you’re not just enjoying a cake – you’re savoring Romania’s heartfelt history. Ready to have a bite? i impulsively thought of doing this the night before at 10pm, so i sort of just went with it and watched the day unfold without a plan.  what you didn’t see: - me leaving the house 2 hours later than anticipated  - me missing the ferry by 3 minutes and having to wait an hour for the next one - me panicking on the ferry when i checked the hours of the coffee shop and it said it closed in 15 minutes and i was in the middle of the sound… only to learn i was looking at the wrong location (thankfully) - me realizing that i only had an hour on bainbridge before i needed to ferry back to the city  - me feeling a bit lonely throughout the day  - me panicking again thinking i got on the wrong ferry back  solo walking is an adventure!  you really do learn a lot about yourself when you only have you to depend on for navigating cities and ferry schedules.  i also want to say, it’s completely normal to feel bored or lonely when solo walking/traveling. sure, it’s fun to experience new things, but it’s important to note that not every moment is going to be overwhelmingly joyful and that’s okay! #walk #walking #outdoors #outside #seattle #seattlelife #washington #solotravel #pnw #pnwadventures #winter #exercise

save for tips on using cash abroad! 👇  I wasted WAYYY too much money on ATM fees before I learned this trick! 🤑 I am not exaggerating, this can save you $10-$50 per ATM visit depending on how much you’re pulling from the ATM 🏧 as long as you have a debit card that doesn’t charge you a fee to convert currencies, than you’re always better off declining the conversion rate the ATM offers you a few cards that have no foreign transaction fees (there are many out there though!): 💚 @Wise  ❤️ @Capital One 360 Checking 💙 @USAA Checking (the one I use) ATM Steps: ✈️ use a debit card without international transaction fees 💸 go to an ATM on arrival in a country ❌ decline the currency conversion they offer ✅ accept the ATM fee 💳 wait for your cash AND DEBIT CARD I usually bring $100-$200 USD with me JUST in case as a backup, but I’ve yet to ever use it! send to someone who could use this tip! #traveltips #travelhacks #worldtravel #internationaltravel #travelmore #bucketlist #travelexpert #traveltipsandtricks

Die Aussicht vom Bella Vista ist der Hammer! 🤩🏔️ Mit der Gondel schweben wir gemütlich zum malerischen Schwarzsee, der uns ein atemberaubendes Panorama bietet. 💒🌊 Der Weg zur Hütte ist abenteuerlich – von mäßig ansteigend bis schroff und nah am Abgrund. Perfekt für alle, die Nervenkitzel lieben! 😎☝️ Das Panorama wird immer beeindruckender mit Blick auf Dom, Dufourspitze und Breithorn. 🤩 An der Hörnlihütte auf 3.260 m schmeckt das Rösti einfach himmlisch.🍴😋 Noch ein paar Meter weiter und ich kann das Matterhorn berühren.🤝😎 Ob wir es auch zum Gipfel geschafft hätten? 👀 #matterhorn #zermatt #wandern #wanderung #wanderlust #mountains #fypage

Basil Seed Cocktail in Delhi, India 🇮🇳 I visited the Sarojini Nagar Market in South Delhi and stopped by a shop to buy a basil seed juice. When I went to pay with a 100 rupee note, the cashier rejected it, as it had been torn in half and taped back together.  The guy I bought a hat from earlier gave me this note as change. Apparently any torn note in India is useless, no vendor will accept it, and all you can do is take it to the reserve bank of India to get it changed for a new one. #India #Delhi #NewDelhi #Travel #SoloTravel #Desi #TravelAdvice #BudgetTravel #TravelVlog #TravelSafety #StreetFood #IndianFood #IndianCuisine

Spiraled perfection 😋 A chimney cake, also known as Kürtőskalács in Hungarian, is a delightful Eastern European pastry with a unique twist.  Imagine a golden brown, crispy cylinder of pastry, hollow on the inside like a chimney (hence the name!). It's typically about the size of your forearm and has a spiral pattern from being wrapped around a special rolling pin or spit.  Traditionally, chimney cakes are enjoyed plain or dusted with cinnamon sugar or ground walnuts. Modern variations go wild, offering toppings like chocolate, fruit, ice cream, and even savory options like cheese and herbs. 🎥 In our latest video, we dive deep into the remarkable story of the Mothers of Plaza de Mayo, a group of courageous women who stood up against Argentina's military dictatorship in a powerful display of resilience and love. During a time when gathering in public was severely restricted and cultural expressions like tango and carnival were banned, these brave mothers found a way to protest peacefully. They gathered every Thursday in front of the Casa Rosada, creatively circumventing restrictions by walking arm in arm in circles to demand answers about their disappeared children. Their struggle is a poignant reminder of the power of peaceful protest and the enduring strength of maternal love. Despite facing the same grim fate as their children, the Mothers of Plaza de Mayo remain a symbol of resistance and hope, continuing their demonstrations to this day. Their story is not just history; it's a call to remember the sacrifices made for human rights and justice. Watch the full story and be inspired by their unwavering determination. Anyways, to the deets!  PRICE: 365 rand pp (aka $26 CAD), drinks not included For the full menu you can look it up on their website, it’s quite the list but you get the idea from the video. There’s a bar where you can order all the wine and drinks you desire (we love that), and in between courses you can hit the beach or check out what they’re cooking up at the braai pit. Share this with someone you want to take for hot chocolate in Paris 🍫 Every once in a while, I remember this hot chocolate in Paris, and suddenly I have a strong urge to buy a train ticket 😄 Since 1927, Carette has been a go-to for both locals and travelers seeking warmth and comfort through their taste buds. While it's a super famous place, I really do think it's worth it. Their pastries, breakfast, and hot chocolate are so worth the hype! There are multiple locations, but the one I visited is right across from the Trocadero. It's super convenient after exploring the Eiffel Tower. Pro tip: Go early since it does get quite busy. 🕗 While I've only tried hot chocolate at Carette, there are many other popular places. One day, I'll try them all and have the ultimate ranking. Some other options include: 🍫 Angelina 🍫 Les Deux Magots 🍫 Cafe de Flore 🍫 Jean-Paul Hévin Tag your chocolate-tasting accomplice! Have you ever tasted the delicious traditional Romanian cuisine? First up, we have “carnati”, a popular Romanian sausage made from ground pork mixed with a blend of spices, such as garlic and paprika. What makes these sausages truly unique is the use of pig fat, which gives them a rich and smoky flavor. Watch as we show you how to prepare these juicy and flavorful sausages over an open fire, just like the locals do. Next, we have the mouth-watering traditional cheeses of Romania, such as “telemea” and “burduf”. Telemea is a salty and crumbly cheese that’s commonly used in salads and sandwiches, while Burduf is a soft and creamy cheese that’s aged in fir tree bark for several weeks, giving it a distinct earthy flavor. These cheeses are an essential part of Romanian cuisine and can be enjoyed on their own or as a part of a delicious dish. So, what are you waiting for? When visiting Detroit, you have to get Detroit-style pizza. A great place to get some is at Buddy's Pizza. My nieces, nephew, and I went to the original location on Conant Street which has been around since 1946. Detroit-style pizza is a rectangular deep dish pizza which has a crispy crust, rich cheese, flavorful toppings, and lots of sauce. Every bite is packed full of flavor. What is great is that everyone can join in the fun as they even have vegan and gluten-free options! Make sure to get the full experience of Buddy's Pizza by bringing your friends and family to join in the fun! I want to give a very special thanks to my nieces and my nephew for coming out to join in the adventure! They are some of my biggest supporters, and I truly appreciate and care for every one of them! #buddyspizza #detroitpizza #detroitstylepizza #detroitfood #detroitrestaurants #puremichigan #detroittravel #visitdetroit #exploredetroit #michiganfood #michiganrestaurants #visitmichigan #exploremichigan #michigantravel #michigantraveler #michiganfoodie #foodietravel #detroitfoodie

🦞Unlimited Lobster every Sunday🦞  At this buffet feast, the star of the show is the mountain of lobsters piled up neatly, already cut in half, so it's super easy to take the meat out.  Regardless, they expect that you will most likely be eating with your hands, so they prepare a cup of water with lemon slices for you to wash your hands. Oh, and they make sure they've got to remind you multiple times, probably because too many people have accidentally drank it instead 😂 There is only 1 buffet station, and it's in the shape of a long oval, with desserts taking up 1 side of the station - and that honestly excited me more than the lobster 🤭 If only I could eat more, I'd love to indulge on all the sweets 🥺 It's £90 for the Ned's Feast, or £155 to also include bottomless champagne, but we're not huge drinkers so we went with the £90 option. These are some of the best foods to try while traveling through Central Europe Wiener Schnitzel- This is considered the national dish of Austria. It’s a crispy veal cutlet t and it’s usually served with potatoes. Goulash - A comforting thick hearty stew of meat and veggies that’s popular all across the Central Europe region.  Chimney Cake- This is a popular Hungarian dessert that you’ll find sold on the street. Apfelstrudel- These are traditional Austrian apple strudels. Make sure to try one of these especially if you're heading to Vienna Koleno-Pork knuckle its super popular in Prague, especially in bars. It's supposed to be really juicy and really delicious. Töltött Káposzta- This Hungarian stuffed cabbage is an absolute must. In Central Europe they're typically prepared with ground meats and tomato sauce.  Sausages- Depending on where you are the sausages are going to have a different name but either way, if you plan on spending time in central Europe you'll want to try some of the sausage varieties while you are there.  Tell us, what other European dishes are on your list? @taila.thecreator  #foodietravel #europeanfood #travelforfood #europeandishes #prague #vienna #hungary #traveltips #traveltoeurope

TRIP TO DAREESALAM 🌅✨ Join me on an unforgettable trip to Dar es Salaam, where I experienced the magic of a sunset at the beautiful Coral Beach and enjoyed a delightful dinner by the sea. 🌊🌴 My adventure began in the afternoon as I arrived at Coral Beach, located on the scenic Msasani Peninsula. The moment I set foot on the sandy shores, I was captivated by the pristine beauty of the Indian Ocean. I spent my time swimming in the crystal-clear waters and exploring the vibrant coral reefs, which made for an incredible snorkeling experience. 🐠🏝️ As the day slowly gave way to evening, I found the perfect spot on the beach to watch the sunset. The sky transformed into a breathtaking canvas of warm hues, with the sun casting a golden glow over the horizon. It was a moment of pure tranquility and awe, a perfect reminder of nature's incredible beauty. 🌞💫 After the mesmerizing sunset, I headed to The Coral Beach Hotel for dinner. The beachfront restaurant offered a fine dining experience with an array of local Tanzanian dishes and international cuisine. I indulged in fresh seafood, Swahili curry, and grilled meats, all while enjoying the soothing sounds of the ocean waves. 🍽️🍤 For those seeking alternative dining options, Dar es Salaam has a variety of fantastic restaurants. The Waterfront Sunset Restaurant & Beach Bar, located nearby, offers a relaxed atmosphere with great seafood and cocktails. Another excellent choice is Cape Town Fish Market, known for its fresh seafood and sushi, set in a chic environment with ocean views. For a unique dining experience, Akemi Revolving Restaurant in the city center provides panoramic views of Dar es Salaam along with a diverse menu. 🍣🍹 After dinner, I took a leisurely walk along the beach under the starry sky. The gentle ocean breeze and the rhythmic sound of the waves created a serene environment perfect for winding down. 🌌🌾 This trip to Dar es Salaam, with its stunning sunset at Coral Beach and delightful dinner by the sea, was an experience I'll cherish forever. If you're looking for a perfect blend of natural beauty, delicious food, and a tranquil atmosphere, I highly recommend a visit to this coastal gem. 🏖️🌺 #DarEsSalaam #CoralBeach #SunsetViews #BeachLife #TravelDiaries #Tanzania #DinnerByTheSea #TravelAdventures #OceanBreeze #NatureLovers #FoodieTravel

This incredible motorcycle runs on water, traveling 100 km on just 1 liter! 
The inventor uses water and roadside wood to generate steam, 
which powers the bike’s wheels. It can reach speeds of 60 km per hour and even has an extra feature—it doubles as a portable kitchen, 
using the heat to cook food while powering the bike. Governments are reportedly concerned about this invention, 
as it threatens oil-dependent economies. With this water-powered motorcycle, the future of transportation could shift dramatically. #creatorsearchinsights

These moments 🥹  While snow cannons in ski resorts artificially extend the ski season, their environmental impact can't be ignored. They consume energy and water, contributing to carbon emissions. However, when compared to the emissions generated by traveling to these destinations, the journey itself often has a far greater environmental footprint. It turns out, the way we get to the slopes might be the biggest climate concern in our winter sports adventures. 🌍🏂 #austria #snowboarding #mountains #winter #slopes #SustainableTravel #EcoAwareness

You can take a train to Tries Karden HBF and then bus to Mörsdorf.  📍From Trier, Koblenz, Cochem - RB 81 / RE 1 ,  📍From Frankfurt - RE 2 + RE 1 Bus No. 🚌  📍From Tries Karden - Bus No. 631 & 742 📍From Kastellaun - Bus No. 630, 631 , 632 ℹ️ Bus stop - Besuchzentrum Geireley  Note: You have to walk for 1.8 - 2 Kms to reach the bridge. 540 D – L'EROE DI TUTTI I GIORNI 🚀✨ BREVE, AGILE E FLESSIBILE 🏞️🚐 Il tuo compagno ideale, se dovesse attraversare le città di questo mondo: Il VANTourer 540 D. Grazie alla sua compattezza e al suo ingegnoso design, offre un'incredibile quantità di spazio di stoccaggio e rimane comunque manovrabile - anche nei vicoli più stretti. E grazie al letto sali e scendi (opzionale) nella parte posteriore, non dovrete fare a meno di nulla quando viaggiate. Hai sempre molto bagaglio o vuoi portare con te la tua nuova bicicletta? Nessun problema! Il letto sali e scendi opzionale è regolabile in continuo, il che significa che la parte posteriore del furgone può essere utilizzata in modo ottimale per il trasporto di oggetti ingombranti. Grazie al riscaldamento a gasolio integrato, le paure e le preoccupazioni per le forniture di gas appartengono al passato. 🔥🌬️ #vantourer540D #camperlife #travelgoals #adventureawaits #vanlife #campervan #exploretheworld #compactcamper #versatile #maneuverable #spaciousinterior #storage #bedsaliscendi #travelwithstyle #luxurytravel #campinglife #outdoorliving #roadtripvibes #freedomonwheels #getaway #nomadiclife #vanlifestyle #vanconversion #travelinspiration #wanderlust #offthegrid #gasheater #travelwithoutlimits #exploreitaly #travelphotography

Part 11 - #49EuroTicketGermany Series  Places To Visit in #Germany  📍Burg Eltz 🏰 Burg Eltz, one of Germany’s most romantic medieval castles, is in a beautiful valley just off the Mosel Valley near the city Koblenz.  ℹ️ BY TRAIN & BUS:  Option 1: You can get off at Hatzenport Station and from there by bus 365 to Car Park 🅿️ 1 There are regional trains from Koblenz, Cochem and Trier.  Option 2: To Moselkern station, and from there you can make your way by taxi or by foot (about a 5km walk). 📍How To Reach Castle from Car Parking: Option 1: Hike both ways ( It takes around 45 minutes to 1 hour one way ) Option 2: Burgenbus 330 (Castle Bus) from the parking lot to/from Burg Eltz Do check the reel to know about entrance tickets and opening hours. Texel saai? Ik dacht het niet!  𝗧𝗜𝗣𝗦 𝗩𝗢𝗢𝗥 𝗘𝗘𝗡 𝗖𝗨𝗟𝗜𝗡𝗔𝗜𝗥 𝗪𝗘𝗘𝗞𝗘𝗡𝗗 𝗢𝗣 𝗧𝗘𝗫𝗘𝗟 Wat je kunt doen in 48-uur op het eiland? Met deze culinaire tips is het perfecte weekend op Texel al voor je uitgestippeld. » 𝗪𝗶𝗹𝗱𝗲 𝗼𝗲𝘀𝘁𝗲𝗿𝘀 𝗽𝗹𝘂𝗸𝗸𝗲𝗻 𝗼𝗽 𝗵𝗲𝘁 𝗪𝗮𝗱 Geloof mij dat deze oesters nog beter smaken, omdat je er zelf veel moeite voor hebt gedaan. Check het getij en ga bij laag water naar kunstwerk ‘De Schicht’. Daar ligt voor de kust een oesterbank. Nat ga je zeker worden, maar het is zó de moeite waard.  » 𝗖𝗵𝗲𝗰𝗸-𝗶𝗻: 𝗗𝘂𝘁𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗻 𝗗𝘂𝘆𝗻𝘇𝗼𝗼𝗺 Een mooi vakantiehuis op Texel? Google maar eens op het kleinschalige vakantiepark Dutchen Duynzoom. Prachtige moderne villa’s waar je met 8 personen kunt slapen. Met een compleet uitgeruste keuken en open haard en een fijn buiten. Wij borrelden er na een dag op het eiland met onze eigen oesters Rockefeller! » 𝗦𝘁𝗲𝗿𝗿𝗲𝗻𝗱𝗶𝗻𝗲𝗿 𝗕𝗶𝗷 𝗝𝗲𝗳* Het (tot nu toe) enige restaurant op het eiland met een Michelin-ster en iedere keer dat we hier eten is het weer een feestje. De mooiste producten van het eiland als kunstwerkjes op je bord. » 𝗕𝗼𝗿𝗿𝗲𝗹𝗲𝗻 𝗯𝗶𝗷 𝗱𝗲 𝗧𝗲𝘅𝗲𝗹𝘀𝗲 𝗕𝗶𝗲𝗿𝗯𝗿𝗼𝘂𝘄𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗷 De Texelse Bierbrouwerij is een leuke plek om te gaan borrelen. Bestel de bierproeverij zodat je alles kunt proeven! » 𝗭𝗲𝗲𝗵𝗼𝗻𝗱𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗼𝗰𝗵𝘁 𝘃𝗮𝗻𝘂𝗶𝘁 𝗢𝘂𝗱𝗲𝘀𝗰𝗵𝗶𝗹𝗱 Dit is zó leuk om te doen. Boek een zeehondentocht met een ribboot vanuit Oudeschild. Het ritje alleen is al de moeite waard! Het spotten van de zeehonden is de kers op de taart. » 𝗔𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗶𝘁𝗶𝘃𝗼 𝗯𝗶𝗷 𝗢𝘂𝗱𝗲𝗹𝗮𝗻𝗱 Eén van de nieuwere restaurants op het eiland en een must-visit! De volgende keer gaan we hier uitgebreider tafelen, want het ‘Eitje Oudeland’ met ei van eigen kippen gevuld met flan van groene asperge, crème fraîche, aardappelkaantjes en bieslook smaakt naar meer.  » 𝗨𝗶𝘁𝗴𝗲𝗯𝗿𝗲𝗶𝗱 𝘁𝗮𝗳𝗲𝗹𝗲𝗻 𝗯𝗶𝗷 𝗛𝗲𝘁 𝗞𝗼𝗼𝗸𝗮𝘁𝗲𝗹𝗶𝗲𝗿 Ga de 2e avond op Texel uitgebreid dineren bij restaurant Het Kookatelier bij Op Oost. Het restaurant ziet er niet alleen heel mooi uit, je eet er ook ontzettend goed. Dit is een restaurant om in de gaten te houden, want ze hebben nog zoveel mooie groene plannen. Het menu wisselt met de seizoenen en binnenkort gaat het herfstmenu in. Sluit je weekend af met een wandeling bij De Slufter en pak daarna weer de boot naar het vaste land. Ik was een weekendje weg met vrienden, maar dit culinaire weekend is ook perfect met zijn tweetjes <3!  Save deze tips voor je volgende weekendje weg naar Texel. Heb je zelf nog een Texel tip? SAVE THIS if you’re looking for a special place to celebrate without breaking the bank - Restaurant Hubert has one of my favourite happy hour specials in Sydney! ✨🥰 Hubert’s is a French establishment with a warm, quiet luxury that lends itself to European speakeasy vibes. To eat here regularly usually costs quite a pretty penny - but a more affordable way to experience the beauty of the venue is to simply visit during Apéritif Hour! 🍷✨ From $7 G&Ts, small plates around $10 and juicy burgers for under $20, Hubert’s definitely has one of the happiest hours in Sydney’s CBD. We got: ✨ duck parfait with maple jelly- my absolute FAV, I often visit just to get this. It’s SO buttery and tasty, so unique!  ✨ fleur de courgette - zucchini flowers deep fried and crispy, so perfect!  ✨ Normandy burger - juicy patty with melted cheese and pickle on the side. I love the charred taste of the burger. Often I split the burger with a friend after eating all the other plates and it’s perfect! ✨ fries - perfectly crispy fries with the char.  Would highly recommend a visit!  📍 restaurant hubert  sydney, CBD apéritif hour 5pm-6pm daily $$ Whether you’re catching up with a mate after work or celebrating a birthday like we were, definitely check out Restaurant Hubert’s. You won’t regret it!  p.s. Do your best to line up around 4:30pm to secure a seat, it definitely gets busy during a workday ✨🥰 #happyhoursydney #sydneyfoodie #sydneyeats #sydneycbd #foodietravel #sydneyfoodblogger #friendship #frenchcuisine #discoverunder5k

🌿🏕️ Sanctuary Olonana: Luxury and Sustainability on the Banks of the Mara River 🦁🌍 Set along the serene banks of the Mara River in Kenya’s iconic Masai Mara, Sanctuary Olonana is a luxurious safari camp that offers an immersive blend of comfort, culture, and conservation. This award-winning camp is renowned not only for its stunning design and eco-conscious ethos but also for its proximity to one of the world’s most extraordinary wildlife spectacles—the Great Migration. Each of the camp’s elegant suites is designed to bring the outside in, featuring floor-to-ceiling glass doors that offer sweeping views of the Mara River, where hippos and other wildlife can often be seen from your private deck. The contemporary decor, with local influences and natural materials, ensures a seamless blend of luxury and the untamed wilderness that surrounds you. At Sanctuary Olonana, guests are invited to experience thrilling game drives, walking safaris, and cultural interactions with the Maasai people, all while staying in harmony with nature. The camp is dedicated to sustainability, from its eco-friendly construction to community-driven conservation efforts, making it a model for responsible luxury travel. Sometimes I still have to pinch myself when we find dreamy park-ups like this one 🌿✨ Sustainable travel looks different for everyone, and it can feel challenging to choose eco-friendly options when you’re on a tight budget. Before we had the van, even the cheapest hotels were out of reach thanks to inflated prices, and most of our money went towards taking the train instead of flying. In fact, I can count the holidays I’ve had in the last decade on one hand. Our only real option was the occasional multi-day hike, and even then, much of the time was spent navigating bus routes just to get across the country. One of the things I love the most about travelling in our little home on wheels is that it lets us contribute more directly to local economies. The money we save on accommodation goes to local bookshops, cozy cafés, and the occasional tourist spot to help maintain natural areas. Plus, working remotely means we can schedule our adventures with less hassle and earn money on the road 🚐 We often get questions about wild camping in the van, and yes — it’s totally doable! In our last 6 months of van life, we haven’t stayed at a single campsite. Our strategy during the busier months of the year has been to hike in the mornings whenever we can, and drive in the afternoons to snag the perfect spot before anyone else. Solar power has been pretty much limitless in the summer (though we’re getting more mindful now as autumn sets in), and for water, we just visit campsites on the way and offer a small donation. Would you want to wake up here? ✨ 📍Portree, Isle of Skye, Scotland  #VanLife #TinyHomeOnWheels #SustainableTravel #BudgetTravel

When in Greece, your taste buds are in for a treat! 🇬🇷 Here are 10 must-try Greek foods that will make your vacation unforgettable: 1. Greek Salad: Fresh, vibrant, and bursting with flavor, this iconic dish combines juicy tomatoes, crisp cucumbers, onions, olives, and feta, drizzled with olive oil. 2. Fried Calamari: Lightly battered and fried to golden perfection, these tender squid rings are a seafood lover's dream. 3. Kolokythokeftedes: These zucchini fritters are crispy on the outside and soft inside, packed with herbs and feta—a perfect appetizer! 4. Dakos: A Cretan specialty, this barley rusk topped with tomatoes, feta, olives, and oregano is a crunchy, savory delight. 5. Taramosalata: This creamy dip made from fish roe is a salty, tangy spread that pairs perfectly with fresh bread. 6. Marinated Anchovies: These flavorful little fish are marinated in olive oil, vinegar, and herbs—a true Mediterranean treat. 7. Fava: A smooth yellow split pea puree, often served with onions and olive oil, representing the simplicity and heart of Greek cuisine. 8. Greek Yogurt with Spoon Sweets: Thick, creamy yogurt topped with preserved fruits known as spoon sweets is a refreshing and sweet finish to any meal. 9. Loukoumades: These honey-soaked doughnut balls are a favorite dessert, crispy on the outside and fluffy inside. 10. Greek Wine: Don’t miss out on a glass of local wine, whether it’s a crisp Assyrtiko or a bold Agiorgitiko—Greek wines are the perfect complement to your culinary adventure! Cape Winelands Experience with the Red Bus Tram Hope on – Hop off wine tasting experience.  Full day Tour  From $55pp Depart from Cape Town in a luxury air-conditioned coach and head directly to the Franschhoek valley to join the Franschhoek hop-on hop-off wine tram and bus. The Franschhoek Wine Tram offers two hop-on hop-off lines (clockwise & anti-clockwise), each visiting various wine estates in the Franschhoek Valley. Enjoy transportation to each wine estate every hour by a combination of tram and tram-buses around the loop. Each stop is at a different wine estate, allowing you to hop on and hop off at any of the estates. The tram or tram passes each stop once an hour, so you can explore at your convenience to move from one estate to the next. Head back to the Franschhoek Wine Tram station for your transfer back to Cape Town You can select from five different routes, each of which takes you to various wine estates that highlight different aspects of the Franschhoek Valley. With the Hop-on Hop-off experience, you have the freedom to design and organize your own day. You can decide how much time you want to spend at each location (within the line's schedule, naturally), where you want to dine, where you want to enjoy some wine, and which activities you'd like to participate in. Your adventure commences at either the Franschhoek Terminal or the Groot Drakenstein Terminal, depending on the route you've chosen. While you wait for your journey to commence, you can grab a coffee, savor a beignet, and explore our selection of merchandise.
